:::
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
n = 100

data <- data.frame(
  a = rnorm(n, 0, 1),
  b = rnorm(n, 0, 1)
)

t <- t.test(data$a,data$b)

t$p.value
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 0.8422394
```


:::
:::



Now let's repeat that procedure 1000 times. The easiest way to do that is to make a function that returns the information you want. 



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
tPower <- function() {
  n = 100

  data <- data.frame(
    a = rnorm(n, 0, 1),
    b = rnorm(n, 0, 1)
  )

  t <- t.test(data$a,data$b)

  return(t$p.value)
}

tPower()
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 0.4182831
```


:::
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mySample <- data.frame(
  p = replicate(10000, tPower())
) 

mySample %>%
  ggplot(aes(p)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20, boundary = 0)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](power_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-4-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mean(mySample$p < .05)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 0.0475
```


:::
:::



What if you induced a small effect of 0.2 SD?



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
tPower2 <- function() {
  n = 100

  data <- data.frame(
    a = rnorm(n, 0, 1),
    b = rnorm(n, 0.2, 1)
  )

  t <- t.test(data$a,data$b)

  return(t$p.value)
}

tPower2()
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 0.1845265
```


:::
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mySample2 <- data.frame(
  p = replicate(10000, tPower2())
) 

mySample2 %>%
  ggplot(aes(p)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20, boundary = 0)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](power_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-7-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mean(mySample2$p < .05)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 0.2913
```


:::
:::



Hmm, you only get a p-value less than .05 30% of the time. That means that your study would only have 30% power to detect an effect this big with 100 subjects. Let's make a new function to give you the p-value of a study with any number of subjects (you put the N inside the parentheses of the function).



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
tPowerN <- function(n) {

  data <- data.frame(
    a = rnorm(n, 0, 1),
    b = rnorm(n, 0.2, 1)
  )

  t <- t.test(data$a,data$b)

  return(t$p.value)
}

tPowerN(200)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 0.004880657
```


:::
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mySampleN <- data.frame(
  p200 = replicate(10000, tPowerN(200))
) 

mySampleN %>%
  ggplot(aes(p200)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20, boundary = 0)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](power_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mean(mySampleN$p200 < .05)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 0.5098
```


:::
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
nlist <- seq(200, 1000, by = 100)

remove(mySampleN)
for (n in nlist) {
  temp <- data.frame(
    n = n,
    p = replicate(1000, tPowerN(n))
  ) 

  if (exists("mySampleN")) {
    mySampleN <- rbind(mySampleN, temp)
  } else {
    mySampleN <- temp
  }
  remove(temp)
  print(n)
}
```

